[
  {
    "ruleId": "R19",
    "pass": false,
    "severity": "blocking",
    "evidence": "beat-02 script: the visual paragraph introducing the probe and candidates states 'under each candidate a lilac score bar with a numeric readout sits at its current value' — this appears in the same beat, before the next visual paragraph ('A freeze frame carries the prediction card before anything moves') that poses 'which candidate ends up on top, and does any score go negative?'. Real numeric scores are already on screen before the prediction is asked, so the guess is answerable by reading the bars rather than by reasoning, turning the prompt into rhetorical filler.",
    "suggestion": "Hold the score-bar readouts at blank/unlabeled state (bars present but numberless, or bars hidden) until after the prediction card has been posed and held; reveal numeric values only once the sweep begins."
  },
  {
    "ruleId": "R3",
    "pass": false,
    "severity": "advisory",
    "evidence": "spine's locked color registry assigns amber to 'the probe (the thing asking)' and periwinkle to 'the candidates (the data interrogated)'. In beat-01, both the listener's-taste column and the song column have their paired entries light up in periwinkle ('paired entries light up in periwinkle'), with no amber used for the taste/probe-analog list. This pre-establishes periwinkle as a shared color for both roles, which conflicts with the amber/periwinkle split the session relies on from beat-02 onward.",
    "suggestion": "In beat-01, light the taste-column entries in amber (the probe role) and the song-column entries in periwinkle (the candidate role), so the color-to-concept mapping is consistent from the very first frame the learner sees."
  }
]

